{{Infobox language |name=Lahuli–Spiti |states=[[India]] |region=[[Himachal Pradesh]] |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |speakers={{sigfig|30,300|2}} |date=1996–2000 |ref=e18 |fam2=[[Tibeto-Kanauri languages|Tibeto-Kanauri]] ? |fam3=[[Bodish languages|Bodish]] |fam4=[[Tibetic languages|Tibetic]] |lc1=sbu|ld1=Stod Bhoti |lc2=spt|ld2=Spiti Bhoti, Nyam |lc3=cna|ld3=Changthang |lc4=nes|ld4=Bhoti Kinnauri |lc5=tpq|ld5=Tukpa |lc6=jda|ld6=[[Jad language|Jad]] |glotto=laha1255 |glottorefname=Lahauli–Spiti }}
The '''Lahuli–Spiti languages''' or '''Western Innovative Tibetan languages''' are a subgroup of the [[Tibetic languages]] spoken in the [[Lahaul and Spiti district|Lahaul and Spiti]] region of [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[India]]. They are more closely related to [[Standard Tibetan]] than to the neighboring [[Ladakhi–Balti languages]] spoken further north.
According to Tournadre (2005),<ref>N. Tournadre (2005) "L'aire linguistique tibétaine et ses divers dialectes." ''Lalies'', 2005, n°25, p.&nbsp;7–56 [http://tournadre.nicolas.free.fr/fichiers/2005-aire.pdf]</ref> the Lahuli–Spiti languages include: *Lahuli (Stod Bhoti) *Spiti *Nyamkat *Changthang
Bhoti Kinnauri and Tukpa (Nesang) may also belong here.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
