[[Polygamy|Polygamous unions]] are legal in the [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref name="Publishing2006">{{cite book|last=Publishing|first=Explorer|title=Dubai: The Complete Residents' Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=II2bdl4gcIMC&pg=PA25|accessdate=8 April 2013|date=2006-11-30|publisher=Explorer Publishing & Distribution|isbn=9789768182760|pages=25–}}</ref><ref name="Incorporated2008">{{cite book|last=Incorporated|first=Facts On File,|title=United Arab Emirates|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WpPRVVxQDxUC&pg=PA65|accessdate=8 April 2013|year=2008|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9781438105840|pages=65–}}</ref> and like most traditionalist Islamic nations, frequently practiced and often encouraged{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}. Muslim polygamy, in practice and law, differs greatly throughout the Islamic world. In some Muslim countries, polygamy is relatively common, while in most others, it is often rare or non-existent. Polygamy is most widely practiced by Muslims in West Africa (where it is also widely practiced by non-Muslims), as well as in certain traditionalist Arabian states such as Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates.

As with [[polygyny in Islam]] in general, men are allowed up to four wives, and women are not permitted multiple husbands.<ref name=Publishing2006/>

